---
import type { MarkdownInstance } from "astro";
import LineItem from "../components/LineItem.astro";
import PageHeading from "../components/PageHeading.astro";
import ContentSection from "../components/ContentSection.astro";
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

interface Post {
	page: string;
	description: string;
	title: string;
	thumbnail: string;
	thumbnail_dark: string;
	heroImage: string;
	heroImage_dark: string;
	info: string;
}
const posts = Object.values(
	import.meta.glob<MarkdownInstance<Post>>("./posts/*.md", { eager: true }),
);
---

<Layout>
	<PageHeading>My Workflow</PageHeading>
	<ContentSection gap={4}>
		<p>
			Over the past few years my development workflow has shifted pretty heavily
			towards the terminal. I've found that the learning curve of CLI tools,
			while steep, is often worth the experience. Speed and flexibility are two
			attributes I've come to value most in tools, and the CLI variations of
			developer tools tend to prioritize those values.
		</p>
		<p class="w-full">
			These are a few of the tools that have become a staple in my day to day.
		</p>
		<ul class="w-full flex flex-col gap-3 cursor-pointer">
			{posts.map((post) => {
				return (
				<LineItem title={post.frontmatter.title} description={post.frontmatter.description} page={post.frontmatter.page} prefix="posts" />
			)
			})}
		</ul>
		<p>
			These tools require a fair amount of configuration. If you're curious how
			I set mine up or you're looking for a jumping off point, you can take a
			look at my
			<a
				href="https://github.com/jdela22/dotfiles"
				target="_blank"
				class="decoration-alt hover:text-alt transition-all duration-500 underline underline-offset-2"
				>dotfiles</a
			>. I keep them pretty up-to-date for my own use when setting up new
			machines.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>
</Layout>
